Euro Approaches Four-Month High Against Dollar Before ECB Rates Decision

-- B y   L u k a n y o   M n y a n d a
-- 
2011-03-03T11:50:09Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-03/euro-approaches-four-month-high-against-dollar-before-ecb-rates-decision.html
The euro traded within a cent of its
strongest level since November against the dollar on speculation
the  European Central Bank  will use its policy meeting today to
emphasize its readiness to raise interest rates.  The euro climbed versus 14 of its 16 most-traded
counterparts. European retail sales increased more than
economists predicted in January, the European Union said, before
data tomorrow that may show U.S. employment increased. The ECB
will keep the refinancing rate at 1 percent today, according to
all 53 economists surveyed by Bloomberg.  “The market is going into this meeting long the euro,”
said Gavin Friend, a markets strategist at National Australia
Bank Ltd. in  London . “The bar is set high for Trichet. While
there’s a possibility of some disappointment, we have clear
differences between what the ECB is pursuing and what the  Federal Reserve ” is doing, he said.  The euro traded at $1.3879 as of 11:40 a.m. in London from
$1.3866 in  New York  yesterday, when it reached $1.3891, the
strongest since Nov. 9.  Europe ’s common currency was at 113.45
yen from 113.52 yen. Against the franc, it strengthened 0.2
percent to 1.2827. The dollar bought 81.82 yen from 81.87
yesterday, when it dropped to the weakest since Feb. 4.  The euro has gained 1.4 percent against the dollar since
Feb. 21 when ECB Council member Yves Mersch said the central
bank may raise its 2011 inflation forecast to more than 2
percent from 1.8 percent. Policy makers have kept the benchmark
interest rate at 1 percent since May 2009. The ECB, which aims
to keep annual gains in consumer prices to just below 2 percent,
will publish inflation projections for 2011 and 2012 today after
its monthly policy meeting.  Retail Sales  Retail sales in the euro bloc rose 0.4 percent in January
after falling 0.6 percent the prior month, the EU statistics
office in Luxembourg said today. The median prediction of 16
economists surveyed by Bloomberg was for a 0.3 percent gain.  The Swiss franc declined for a second day against the euro
even as central bank Vice Chairman Thomas Jordan said  Switzerland ’s policy makers don’t see a need to counter gains by
purchasing foreign currencies.  Switzerland’s currency weakened by 0.2 percent to 1.2833
against the euro and was also 0.2 percent weaker versus the
dollar at 92.54 centimes.  “The franc is currently very strong and poses a lot of
problems for Swiss companies,” Jordan told reporters after a
press conference in Bern today. Still, “at the moment there is
no necessity of intervening in the  currency market .”  To contact the reporters on this story:
